         <desc type="context">Codex Vercellensis 158, an ancient book in the Capitulary Library of
            the Cathedral in Vercelli in northwestern Italy, preserves most of a Latin manuscript
            made probably in Italy during the 3rd or 4th century that translates an earlier Greek
            account of Peter‚Äôs apostolic career. This Acts of the Apostle Peter, perhaps entitled
            Œ†œÅŒ¨ŒæŒµŒπœÇ Œ†Œ≠œÑœÅŒøœÖ œÑŒø·ø¶ ·ºÄœÄŒøœÉœÑœåŒªŒøœÖ, was written circa 180-190 C.E. possibly in Asia Minor. It
            recounts Peter‚Äôs activities from the Near East to Italy, his controversy with Simon
            Magus at Rome, his consolidation of the congregation there, and his martydom. In this
            passage, Peter sees a vision of Christ and travels from Jerusalem to Caesarea, where he
            embarks on a ship to Rome captained by the hospitable Theon. There are interesting
            details in this scene of passengers launching out of the harbor.</desc>
         <ab type="edition">Lugentibus autem eis et jejunantibus, iam instruebat deus in futurum
            Petrum in Hierosolymis, adimpletis duodecim annis quod illi praeceperat dominus,
            Christus ostendit illi visionem talem, dicens ei, ‚ÄúPetre, quem tu ejecisti de Iudea
            adprobatum magum Simonem, iterum praeoccupavit vos Romae. Et in brevi scias: omnes enim
            qui in me crediderunt dissolvit astutia sua et inergia sua satanas, cuius virtute se
            adprobat esse. Sed noli moras facere: crastina die profiscere, et ibi invenies navem
            paratam, navigantem in Italiam; et in paucos dies ostendam tibi gratiam meam quae non
            habet invidiam nullam.‚Äù Petrus autem hoc viso monitus, referens fratribus sine mora,
            dicens, ‚ÄúNecesse est me ascendere Romae ad expugnandum hostem et inimicum domini et
            fratrum nostrum.‚Äù Et descendit $Caesaream% et confestim ascendit navem, iam scala
            subducta neque epsimenia imposita. gubernius autem nomine Theon respiciens Petrum dixit,
            ‚ÄúQuaecumque habemus universa tua sunt. quae autem gratia nostra, si suscipiamus hominem
            similem nobis in incerto casu, et non omnia quae habemus nos, communicamus tecum? sed
            tantum nos feliciter navigemus.‚Äù Petrus autem oblationi illius gratias agens, ipse autem
            in navi jejunabat, lugens animo et iterum comfortans se, quod deus dignum eum habuisset
            in ministerio suo ministrum.<note type="discussion">Ed. Lipsius 1891 [cited by
               page-line]</note><note type="corrigenda">epsimenia: Apparent Latin transliteration of
               Greek ·º°œàŒ∑ŒºŒ≠ŒΩŒ±.</note><idno type="CTS-URN"/><ref target=""/></ab>
         <ab type="translation">While they were grieving and fasting, God was already preparing
            Peter at Jerusalem for what was to come. After the twelve years had passed which the
            Lord had enjoined on him, Christ showed to him the following vision, saying, ‚ÄúPeter,
            Simon, whom you expelled from Judaea after having proved him to be a magician, has
            forestalled you a second time in Rome. And in short, all who believed in me Satan has
            perverted by his cunning and his power, whose agent he proves to be. But do not delay.
            Go tomorrow (to Caesaerea), and there you will find a ship ready to sail to Italy. And
            within a few days I will show you my grace, which is boundless.‚Äù Instructed by this
            vision, Peter did not delay to mention it to the brethren and said, ‚ÄúI must go to Rome
            to subdue the enemy and opponent of the Lord and of our brethren.‚Äù And he went down to
            Caesarea and at once boarded the ship, which was ready to sail, with the ladder already
            raised and no provisions (lit. boiled foods) in store. But the steersman named Theon
            looked at Peter and said, ‚ÄúWhatever we have is all yours. What favor are we doing
            ourselves, if we receive a man like ourselves in difficult circumstances, and do not
            share with you everything we have? Let us have a safe voyage.‚Äù Peter thanked him for his
            offer. And he fasted in the ship, being dejected in his mind and yet again comforting
            himself, because God considered him to be a worthy servant in his service.<note
               type="translation">Adapted from Schneemelcher and Wilson 1992 and Elliott
               1993</note><note type="discussion"/><note type="corrigenda"/><idno type="CTS-URN"
               /><ref target=""/></ab>
